# Changelog
## 0.6.1

### Added
- Low-resolution-safe compact main footer
- Full-screen F1 command menu behavior through scrollable help page
- Full-screen scrollable message/error pages
- Temporary startup transcript notice from `remfan1994` in new blank sessions
- Automatic removal of the startup notice when the first user message is sent
- Input-box placeholder text: `Type your chat message here...`
- `MONOCHROME` config key
- `INPUT_PLACEHOLDER` config key
- `STARTUP_NOTICE` config key
- Dim/grey styling for user transcript messages in normal display mode
- Normal/white styling for Gemini transcript output and typed input text
- Documentation for display behavior and low-resolution behavior

### Changed
- Main status/footer no longer tries to display every F-key command on one line
- Help, credits, and error messages no longer use clipping-prone small modals
- Long credits text and Project Lead notice now wrap in a scrollable full-screen page
- The Project Lead notice is now primarily presented as a temporary chat-window transcript item, not only as credits text
- User transcript messages are visually distinguished from Gemini output when monochrome mode is disabled
- Input placeholder is visual only and is never sent to Gemini
- Startup notice is not logged, not stored in memory, and not sent to Gemini
- Menu/error display now owns the screen instead of sharing space with the main status line

### Fixed
- F-key help text being cut off on low-resolution terminals
- Credits notice being clipped before the full Project Lead warning could be read
- Error/status messages visually colliding with menus
- Model-list/network error pages becoming hard to recover from on small displays

### Documentation
- Added DISPLAY AND LOW-RESOLUTION BEHAVIOR section to the man page
- Documented `MONOCHROME`
- Documented `INPUT_PLACEHOLDER`
- Documented `STARTUP_NOTICE`
- Documented the temporary startup notice behavior
- Documented that the startup notice is not logged or sent to Gemini
- Updated limitations for very small terminals

### Notes
- Drag selection remains intentionally delegated to the terminal emulator.
- Mousewheel scrolling and click interactions remain in-app behaviors.
- This is a UI stability and readability release, not an API/transport release.

## 0.6.0

### Added
- User-operated model tester replacing autoscan workflow
- `--test-model <model_id>` command-line test mode
- `t` model-test command inside the F2 model selector
- Session browser opened with F4
- Current-session rename support
- New timestamped session creation from session menu
- Options menu opened with F5
- Config editing UI for MODEL, CONTEXT_TURNS, SESSION_DIR, ATTACHMENT_DIR, EDITOR, MODEL_TEST_PROMPT, and MAX_ATTACHMENT_BYTES
- API-key manager opened with F3
- Runtime-only API-key entry
- Explicit API-key save-to-config action
- Runtime API-key forget action
- Config API-key removal action
- External editor support opened with F8
- EDITOR config key support
- Memory menu opened with F6
- View current memory
- Edit current memory in external editor
- Clear current memory
- Rebuild memory from session log
- Memory snapshots saved into session logs as system entries
- Session resume now prefers latest memory snapshot when available
- File/attachment menu opened with F7
- Local file browser for attaching files to the next prompt
- Text-like file attachment support
- Binary/media inlineData attachment support for Gemini REST requests
- Generated inlineData response attachment saving
- Saved attachment browser and preview
- Credits/about screen opened with F9
- GitHub project URL in credits screen
- Project lead vegetarian notice in credits screen
- Reverse-video header/status styling
- Dim/grey separator and metadata styling
- Mouse-aware list/menu selection reuse across new menus
- MAX_ATTACHMENT_BYTES config key
- MODEL_TEST_PROMPT config key

### Removed
- F4 autoscan behavior
- `--autoscan-model` command-line mode
- Autoscan challenge settings as active behavior
- Automatic probing of every available model

### Changed
- F4 is now the session browser instead of autoscan
- F5 now opens the options menu; Ctrl+G remains the send command
- Model selection workflow now emphasizes user testing and informed activation
- API keys pasted in the interface are runtime-only unless explicitly saved
- Session logs now store explicit context snapshots
- Prompt sending now supports local attachments
- Gemini response parsing now handles text, inlineData, and fileData-style response parts
- UI styling now uses reverse video and dim attributes more consistently

### Documentation
- Updated man page synopsis with `--test-model`
- Removed autoscan documentation
- Added MODEL TESTING section
- Added API KEY STORAGE section
- Added EXTERNAL EDITOR section
- Expanded ATTACHMENT SYSTEM section
- Expanded MEMORY MODEL section
- Added credits/about behavior
- Updated controls section for F1-F9 workflow
- Updated limitations for media attachment dependency on model/API support

### Notes
- Autoscan was removed because probing all models was deemed a questionable workflow.
- The model tester sends one request to one user-selected model and shows the raw response.
- Media attachment support uses Gemini REST inlineData-style request parts and depends on model capability.
## 0.5.0

### Added
- Mouse event support through curses.mousemask
- Mousewheel transcript scrolling in the main chat view
- Left-click input cursor placement in the input area
- Mousewheel navigation in the model selector
- Left-click model row selection in the model selector
- Double-click model activation in the model selector
- Mouse dismissal support for message dialogs
- Mouse-assisted yes/no dialogs
- Mouse-assisted API-key cursor placement
- Layout coordinate tracking for mouse hit detection
- Input segment mapping for click-to-cursor behavior
- Mouse support documentation in the man page

### Changed
- Main event loop now handles curses.KEY_MOUSE
- Input rendering now stores visual segment metadata for mouse cursor placement
- Model selector help text now includes click and double-click behavior
- Message dialogs now indicate they can be dismissed by keypress or click
- Yes/no dialogs now document click behavior
- Status line reports mousewheel transcript scrolling and input cursor placement

### Documentation
- Added MOUSE SUPPORT section to man page
- Documented mousewheel transcript scrolling
- Documented input-area click behavior
- Documented model-selector mouse behavior
- Documented mouse behavior in message and yes/no dialogs
- Updated LIMITATIONS section with terminal-emulator mouse dependency
- Clarified that terminal text selection remains the terminal emulator's responsibility

### Notes
- Mousewheel support commonly appears as BUTTON4/BUTTON5 in curses-compatible terminals.
- Mouse behavior depends on terminal emulator support.
- Drag selection and mouse-based transcript text selection are intentionally not implemented in this release.

## 0.4.0

### Added
- `CONTEXT_TURNS` config key for clearer conversation-memory terminology
- Backward compatibility for legacy `HISTORY_LIMIT` config key
- Autoscan challenge validation
- Default autoscan prompt: `What is the capital of Texas?`
- Default autoscan expected substring: `austin`
- `AUTOSCAN_PROMPT` config key
- `AUTOSCAN_EXPECTED` config key
- Autoscan failure reporting when a model returns text but fails the expected-answer check

### Changed
- Autoscan no longer accepts any non-empty text response as success
- Autoscan now requires the response to contain the expected answer substring
- Internal memory variable renamed from history-style terminology to context-buffer terminology
- `CONTEXT_TURNS` now represents user/assistant exchanges rather than individual log entries
- Resume memory rebuild now keeps up to `CONTEXT_TURNS * 2` speaker entries from the session log
- Man page now describes `HISTORY_LIMIT` as a legacy alias instead of the preferred setting

### Documentation
- Updated CONFIGURATION section with `CONTEXT_TURNS`
- Documented legacy `HISTORY_LIMIT`
- Added autoscan challenge details
- Documented `AUTOSCAN_PROMPT`
- Documented `AUTOSCAN_EXPECTED`
- Updated MEMORY MODEL section
- Updated MODEL AUTOSCAN section
- Updated LIMITATIONS section to clarify autoscan verifies only the configured challenge

### Notes
- The autoscan challenge is intentionally empirical and configurable.
- The default Texas/Austin challenge is used to reduce false positives from models that merely return any non-empty text.
- This update does not change the Bash implementation; Bash parity should be handled in the next Bash-specific revision.

## 0.3.0

### Added
- F4 model autoscan inside the ncurses interface
- `--autoscan-model` command-line autoscan mode
- Empirical model testing with a minimal prompt
- Autoscan progress display in the status bar
- Optional config saving after F4 autoscan selection
- Optional config saving after F2 manual model selection
- `i` model-info view inside the F2 model selector
- Fallback model labeling when no MODEL is configured
- Config update helper for saving selected MODEL values
- Autoscan documentation in comments and man page

### Changed
- The model default is now treated as a fallback, not a permanent recommendation
- `MODEL` may be unset; the UI labels the fallback clearly
- Model selection is now more future-resistant because autoscan tests live API behavior
- F2 model selector now exposes API metadata through the info view
- Header now displays fallback state when no explicit MODEL is configured

### Documentation
- Added `--autoscan-model` to man page synopsis
- Added MODEL AUTOSCAN section
- Expanded MODEL DISCOVERY section
- Documented F4 autoscan control
- Documented autoscan API-call cost
- Documented that autoscan finds a functional model, not necessarily the best model
- Documented persistence behavior for F2 and F4 model choices

### Notes
- Autoscan tests models in the order returned by the Gemini models endpoint.
- Autoscan does not rely on hardcoded future model-name assumptions.
- The fallback model remains `gemini-2.5-flash`, but it is now explicitly labeled as a fallback.



## 0.2.0

### Added
- F2 in-app model selector
- `--models` command-line model listing
- Gemini model discovery through the v1beta models endpoint
- Filtering of listed models to generateContent-compatible models
- F3 API-key setup inside the interface
- Startup API-key prompt when no key is configured
- Optional saving of pasted API key to config file
- Optional saving of selected model to config file
- Config update helper for writing KEY=VALUE entries
- Config-file permission hardening attempt with chmod 0600
- Visual input wrapping inside the ncurses input area
- Model change notices in transcript
- Model selector modal with keyboard navigation
- API-key input modal with masked display
- Yes/no confirmation modal
- Message modal for errors and status notices

### Changed
- Input display now wraps visually inside the input box instead of relying on terminal line wrapping
- Status bar now documents F2 model selector and F3 API-key setup
- Send behavior remains Ctrl+G/F5
- API-key absence no longer forces immediate shell-level failure; the TUI can prompt for a key
- Model IDs are normalized so both `gemini-x` and `models/gemini-x` forms are accepted
- Help and man page now document model discovery

### Documentation
- Updated man page synopsis with `--models`
- Added MODEL DISCOVERY section
- Added API KEY SETUP section
- Updated controls documentation
- Documented F2 model selector
- Documented F3 API-key setup
- Documented visual input wrapping
- Documented API-key precedence

### Notes
- Ctrl+G remains the primary send key in curses because it is easy to detect and avoids conflict with Enter-as-newline behavior.
- The Bash edition should receive a matching `--models` feature and documentation update in its next synchronized revision.



## 0.1.0

### Added
- Initial Python ncurses implementation
- Full-screen terminal interface
- Scrollable transcript window
- Multiline input box
- Proper cursor movement inside input
- Backspace support across logical input lines
- Horizontal scrolling for long input lines
- F5 send shortcut
- Ctrl+G send shortcut
- F10 quit shortcut
- Ctrl+Q quit shortcut
- PgUp/PgDn transcript scrolling
- Ctrl+U input clearing
- Ctrl+L redraw support
- Named session support
- Timestamped session log support
- Resume support
- Session listing
- Version flag
- Built-in help through argparse
- Shared config support with Bash version
- GEMINI_API_KEY environment/config support
- Configurable SESSION_DIR support
- Configurable ATTACHMENT_DIR support
- Rolling memory context
- Memory rebuild from resumed session logs
- Attachment extraction for fenced markdown code blocks
- Language-aware attachment file extensions
- Attachment numbering that avoids overwriting previous files
- JSON request construction using Python json.dumps
- Gemini API transport through Python standard library urllib

### Changed
- Input handling moved from shell stdin to ncurses-managed editor
- Terminal redraw behavior moved from line output to full-screen interface
- API payload construction no longer depends on shell string escaping
- Session names are sanitized for filesystem safety

### Documentation
- Added gemini-curses(1) man page
- Documented controls
- Documented shared config behavior
- Documented attachment system
- Documented session name sanitization
- Documented known limitations

### Notes
- This is the first usable ncurses release.
- The Bash version remains useful as the lightweight fallback implementation.
